In this process, cathode is attached to the negative terminal of the battery so it is negatively charged whereas anode is attached to the positive terminal of the battery so it has positive charge. During electrolysis, $\mathrm{Cu}^{2+}$ ion of $\mathrm{CuSO}_{4}$ used as an electrolyte reaches the cathode and get reduced by receiving electrons from the cathode terminal.
$$
\text { Cathode : } \quad \mathrm{Cu}^{2+}+2 \mathrm{e}^{-} \longrightarrow \begin{gathered}
\mathrm{Cu} \\
\text { Copper metal }
\end{gathered}
$$
Resulted copper metal is deposited on the cathode. The impure anode is oxidised to the $\mathrm{Cu}^{2+}$ ions by leasing electrons hence anode is dissolved into the electrolyte.
$$
\text { Anode }: \mathrm{Cu} \longrightarrow \mathrm{Cu}^{2+}+2 \mathrm{e}^{-}
$$
Therefore, the pure metal from the impure anode dissolves into the electrolyte that means it becomes thinner and thinner whereas an equivalent amount of pure metal from the electrolyte is deposited on the cathode that means it becomes thicker and thicker.

(b) This process is also called auto reduction process or air reduction process. The sulphide ores of less electropositive metals are heated in air to convert part of the ore into oxide or sulphate which then react with the remaining sulphide ore to give the metal and sulphur dioxide.
$$
\begin{aligned}
& 2 \mathrm{Cu}_{2} \mathrm{~S}+3 \mathrm{O}_{2} \longrightarrow 2 \mathrm{Cu}_{2} \mathrm{O}+2 \mathrm{SO}_{2} \\
& \mathrm{Cu}_{2} \mathrm{~S}+2 \mathrm{Cu}_{2} \mathrm{O} \longrightarrow 6 \mathrm{Cu}+\mathrm{SO}_{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

Cinnabar $(\mathrm{HgS})$ is an ore of mercury. When cinnabar is heated in air, it is first converted into HgO and on further heating reduces into Hg .
$$
\begin{gathered}
2 \mathrm{HgS}+3 \mathrm{O}_{2} \xrightarrow{\Delta} 2 \mathrm{HgO}+2 \mathrm{SO}_{2} \\
2 \mathrm{HgO} \xrightarrow{\Delta} 2 \mathrm{Hg}+\mathrm{O}_{2}
\end{gathered}
$$

Metals are electropositive elements because they lose electrons very easily to form positively charged ions.
$$
\begin{gathered}
\mathrm{K} \rightarrow \mathrm{~K}^{+}+\mathrm{e}^{-} \\
\mathrm{Mg} \rightarrow \mathrm{Mg}^{2+}+2 \mathrm{e}^{-}
\end{gathered}
$$

Zn is above hydrogen while copper is below hydrogen in the activity series of metals. Therefore, zinc displaces hydrogen from dilute HCl while copper does not.
$$
\begin{gathered}
\mathrm{Zn}(\mathrm{~s})+2 \mathrm{HCl}(\mathrm{aq}) \rightarrow \mathrm{ZnCl}_{2}(\mathrm{aq})+\mathrm{H}_{2}(\mathrm{~g}) \\
\mathrm{Cu}(\mathrm{~s})+2 \mathrm{HCl}(\mathrm{aq}) \rightarrow \text { No reaction }
\end{gathered}
$$

(i) A is carbon, B is carbon monoxide and C is carbon dioxide.
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathrm{C}(\mathrm{~s})+\mathrm{O}_{2}(\mathrm{~g}) \longrightarrow \underset{(\mathrm{C})}{\mathrm{CO}_{2}(\mathrm{~g})} \\
& \mathrm{C}(\mathrm{~s})+\frac{1}{2} \mathrm{O}_{2}(\mathrm{~g}) \longrightarrow \underset{(\mathrm{B})}{\mathrm{CO}(\mathrm{~g})}
\end{aligned}
$$
(ii) A belongs to Group -14 of the periodic table.

